Introduction

In this project, we will be analyzing dataset that contains informations from The Movie Database(TMDb). What can we say about a movie after it is released. Here are the steps we will be taking: Step 1:the following questions will be the focus of my analysis: -what is the relationship between popularity, budget, revenue, profit and vote count? which genres of movies are the most released over the year? -which director directed most movies? -which actor and actress casted in most movies? which genre of movies are the most popular?
-which movies(genre and original title) are the highest and lowest revenue? -which movies(genre and original title) are the highest and lowest budget? -Which movie(genre and original title) is the most successfull? Step 2:data wrangling We are going to load and assess the data; then, we will make some modifications to ensure that our data is clean and ready for analysis. Step3: data exploration We will look for relationship, correlation , and patterns regarding the dataset by dranwing some visualizations. Step 4: conclusions and limitations We will summarize our findings and terminate by mentionning our limitations during our analysis. We will be using python libraries such as pandas, NumPy, matplotlib and seaborn.

Now, we do have some issues with columns genres and cast. Some rows have a combination of genres and cast. I'll create separate dataframes for each: genres and cast in case we need the original df. First, we are going to split up the genres column so we can tally each genre individually. Next, I'll remove the 'genres' column (with multiple values) and replace it with a 'genre' column (with single values). Then I'll make sure that there is a new row for each genre (stacked), so there will be multiple rows with the same original_title.

In [41]:
df_split_genre = df.copy()
split_genre = df_split_genre['genres'].str.split('|').apply(pd.Series, 1
).stack().reset_index(level=1, drop=True)
split_genre.name = 'genre_split'
df_split_genre = df_split_genre.drop(['genres'], axis=1).join(split_genre)

Conclusion

Throught my analysis, I was able to find out the following answers to my questions First,there is a positive correlation between popularity, budget, revenue and profit. Second, the director Woody Allen produced the highest number of movies. Thirth,Robert De Niro and Samuel L. Jackson are the actors who was casted in the most movies. Forth, the movies that are the most produced are drama and comedy. Firth, 'Avatar' is the most successfull movie , under genres Action, Adventure, Fantasy, and Science Fiction under the director James Cameron. Eventhough, I have a positive correlation between popularity, budget, revenue, vote count and profit, the most successfull genres of movies do have the highest amount of revenue but not the highest number in popularity and vote count. The director James Cameron is well known for record breaking titles on the list of the worlds top 10 box office hits:'Titanic' in 1997 has over 2,5 billion of revenue, 'Avatar' in 2009 with 2,79 billion. His last movie this year(2019) 'Avengers: Endgame' is already $2,8 billion after running for only three weeks. What genres of movies will James Cameron make the next most successfull Only three weeks. What genres of movies will James Cameron make the next most successfull?

Limitations

First, the currency was not provided for budget and revenue columns and we assume it is US dollar. Second, there are many missing value NaN and a lot of zero value. We dropped the missing values and replaced the zero values by the mean. These may affect my analysis. For example, when we did {df.loc[df['popularity'].idxmin()]}, We realize that the profit value was wrong . Third,we split the data seperated for genres and cast into list for easy parsing during our cleaning and this can increase the time taken in calculating the result.
